column131: I am not able to understand, beyond broad outlines, how Solid will fit into the context of the larger world in terms of current events, and attempts to do so seem to be discouraged.  This makes me wonder which side of the great divide Solid is on.  That divide is not one of gender or race, but of class, and by that I don't mean your level of educational achievement or how you dress or how you pronounce words, but I mean in the Marxist sense of how you put bread on your table and how you feel about that.  Is Solid aligned with this "great reset" move towards technocracy?  Is Solid planned as the basis of a social credit system with a supposed human face?  I have the feeling that such direct questions are thought polarizing and thus strongly discouraged.  Maybe they *are* polarizing, one percent versus 99 percent.  But for the 99 they need a clear and loud answer to inspire the effort needed to develop software.  For these reasons I feel I don't belong.
column132: To know more about where Solid fits into the larger world
column133: I see the W3C as a corporate dominated body, and as such I think it has and/or will have too much control over Solid, which I see as the emerging web we want, we being the 99% outside corporate decision making.
